  "text": "Increased UFP levels were also associated with classrooms of schools that prepared the children's meals in the building. The act of cooking is documented to produce significant amounts of UFPs due to the combustions involved in the process [CITATION_1] . Many schools in Portugal have poor exhaustion systems in the kitchen and canteens; thus, it is possible that some of these particles penetrate to the classroom environment contributing to the indoor air concentration of UFPs. However, this result needs to be interpreted with caution since there was only one school that cooked meals inside the building during the present study (US5).",
